				<div class="postKicker">
					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Readers Respond: Alone Again, Naturally</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Marie Tessier			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-08-21T20:07:03+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">August 21, 2014 4:07 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">August 21, 2014 4:07 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/08/21/readers-respond-alone-again-naturally/" data-title="Readers Respond: Alone Again, Naturally" data-description="Readers dissected the Obama presidency with waves of disappointment, civic despondency and Democratic party solidarity in comments on Maureen Dowdâs column, âAlone Again, Naturally.â">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Readers dissected the Obama presidency with waves of disappointment, civic despondency and Democratic party solidarity in response to Maureen Dowdâs column Wednesday about President Obamaâs man-apart style, â<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/20/opinion/maureen-dowd-alone-again-naturally.html?ref=opinion">Alone Again, Naturally</a>.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âHe runs the risk of a Carter legacyâ¦ being a good and decent guy, but ineffective president,â<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/20/opinion/maureen-dowd-alone-again-naturally.html?comments#permid=12602089">Jim Nunn in Cincinnati</a> wrote. âHe darn well needs to give it his all until the curtain closes.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Progressive readers frequently said the president has failed to act strongly enough against corporate abuses. âPresident Obama has broken my heart and spirit,â<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/20/opinion/maureen-dowd-alone-again-naturally.html?comments#permid=12602355">Karla wrote from Mooresville, N.C.</a> âNo one represents the tens of millions of citizens at the bottom, those in need, our children, our future. No one.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Many lament that the gifted candidate-above-the-fray Ms. Dowdâs column describes has not, in their view, performed up to his lofty expectations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âObama has been unable to articulate any cohesive or consistent foreign policy,â<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/20/opinion/maureen-dowd-alone-again-naturally.html?comments#permid=12605225">James D. Benak wrote from Chicago</a>.âWhere are the brilliant solutions we hoped he would bring to foreign &#8211; and domestic &#8211; policy?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nonetheless, hundreds of readers vented frustration with Ms. Dowdâs consistently acerbic assessment of the Obama presidency. Many of these comments, however, were <a href="//www.nytimes.com/content/help/site/usercontent/usercontent.html#usercontent-comments">unpublishable</a>. Other readers suggested she take a broader perspective.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âObama had to deal with two wars going poorly, a global economy in free fall, and a Republican party focusing on stopping him,â<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/20/opinion/maureen-dowd-alone-again-naturally.html#permid=12600017">Steve in Westchester writes</a>.âHe could have been a better leader, but considering the challenges, I think historians will be more realistic than Maureen.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Others pointed to the race-based underpinnings of some opposition to the president.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âHe evokes a virulent racism that I&#8217;d thought we&#8217;d got over in this country,â<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/20/opinion/maureen-dowd-alone-again-naturally.html#permid=12603274">Tom Norris writes from Florida</a>. âWhen we look back on his presidency, maybe we&#8217;ll see that he was a transition in terribly polarized and turbulent times, that he didn&#8217;t do so badly after all.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI have been disappointed in some of the decisions,â<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/20/opinion/maureen-dowd-alone-again-naturally.html?comments#permid=12605583">Obama voter Linda Starnes writes from Redmond, Wash.</a>âHowever, I do not discount the very real, often illogical, opposition to everything he has attempted.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/20/opinion/maureen-dowd-alone-again-naturally.html?comments#permid=12604698">Thom Schwartz</a> in Austin writes that excellent leadership is also extremely controversial. âIt would have been nice for Obama to be able to &#8216;cheerlead the nation&#8217; out of our financial and political funk &#8211; but that &#8230; may have further incited the reactionary right,â Schwartz writes. âLincoln was a great leader, but let us also remember that he was hated by the entire South.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A reader called WattsinChicago says the impact of race on the Obama presidency was predictable, and behooves a unified activism from Democrats and liberals.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWhere are our other champions willing to put niceties, and their potential political futures, aside and stand four-square in opposition to the haters, and those who oppose just to try to turn this moment in our history into a failure?â WattsInChicago writes. âPolitics as usual just won&#8217;t cut it now.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Obamaâs supporters believe the presidentâs cool demeanor is a signal of mature decision making.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âSteady recovery from an economic meltdown, passage of the Affordable Care Actâ¦ extrication from [President] Bush&#8217;s two wars and care in responding to new crises,â<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/20/opinion/maureen-dowd-alone-again-naturally.html?comments#permid=12603821">Bob Walner writes from Boston</a>. âA grown-up presidency.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Others were breezier.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI&#8217;m not disappointed that millions are finally getting health insurance, important steps towards carbon emissions have been taken, and our foreign policy is sane,â<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/20/opinion/maureen-dowd-alone-again-naturally.html?comments#permid=12602347:12604409">Olivia James writes from Boston</a>. âLook at your retirement accounts and take heart &#8211; the stock market has doubled, the economy is strengthening, and a depression which could very well have wiped you out has been averted.â</p>
	</div>
